Title:
Berlin — Cross-platform CPU-based Virtual Machine Detection Framework

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
Berlin is a C library/PoC that detects whether it is running inside a virtual machine by leveraging CPU “vmexit” instructions and timing-based side channels. It targets the problem of avoiding OS/artifact-based VM checks (e.g., registry keys) that create IOCs and are easy to spoof, instead focusing on CPU behavior differences under virtualization. The core API is a single function `int isVM(int threshold);` that returns true when measured execution latency exceeds a configurable threshold (and also returns true on error). The project emphasizes portability by abstracting OS-specific dependencies and being freestanding (no C/C++ runtime requirement), intended for embedding into offensive tooling. It’s primarily useful for red teams, pentesters, and malware developers who want sandbox/VM awareness with fewer host artifacts. It’s interesting because it frames VM detection as “CPU feature emulation best-effort,” using vmexit-induced latency as a cross-platform signal.

Technical Focus:
- VM detection via vmexit-triggering CPU instructions
- Timing attacks / latency measurement for virtualization inference
- Freestanding C implementation (no CRT), portability abstractions
- Threshold tuning and performance/optimization considerations (-O3)
- Anti-analysis / sandbox evasion design tradeoffs

Use Cases:
- Embed VM/sandbox checks into loaders, implants, or droppers
- Reduce reliance on OS-level VM artifacts (registry/files/drivers) to lower IOCs
- Research and benchmarking of vmexit timing characteristics across hypervisors
- Defensive testing: validate whether sandboxes/VMs leak detectable timing signals

Keywords:
virtual machine detection, vmexit, timing attack, side-channel, hypervisor, KVM, QEMU, CPU emulation, anti-analysis, sandbox evasion, freestanding C, no CRT, clang, -O3, threshold calibration, bare metal vs VM, offensive tooling, PoC, cross-platform